message.content: The standard gauge, also known as "Stephenson's gauge" or "broad gauge," is a widely used railway track gauge that measures 1,43762 inches (1,688880 millimeters) between the inner sides of the rails. It was developed by George Stephenson and his son Robert in England during the early 19th century. This gauge became the dominant rail system for many countries around the world due to its versatility and efficiency.
